content.description: Starting in the crack far right on a most excellent jug, traverse left using the crack. There are many variations to this fun problem, however traversing the lip is not one of them. Come on people lets be serious.
content.protection: crash pad, signed legal contract denying responsibility for the shenanigans at the hotel last night.
content.location: Right side of the boulder in the crack. Between the boulder and the prow.

content.description: Sit start on the large left-facing sidepull, and move up through the crack and good crimps to a comfortable lip Dynoing from crack to lip is the V1 Tick Dyno.
content.protection: Flat ground-one pad should be fine, even solo.
content.location: Obvious sidepull smack in the middle of the boulder.

content.description: Start at the left side of the boulder. The top lip is off until you reach the corner on the far right, at which point you will top out right of the prow.
content.protection: crash pad, maybe an imported lager

content.description: Start on the same jug as The Traverse but go straight up angling slightly left using good holds and smalls feet. Â Avoid touching the prow behind you and squeeze your way out to the topout.
content.location: Same start as The Traverse, this is the furthest right problem on the main boulder and to the left of Kiss the Prow.

content.description: Starting in the middle of the boulder there is a wonderful side pull, from said side pull move to the crack, acquire yourself some delicious feet and dyno to the lip straight up. If you choose not to dyno and shimmy your way up on the good crimps the route goes V0.
content.protection: crash pad, good data plan so you can let your mom know where you are.

content.description: Starting with your left hand on the arete and your right on a jug, move straight up to the top of the prow. Don't kiss it though cause that is gross.
content.protection: crash pad, serious mouthwash, chapstick and a rag to clean your lips after kissing the prow.
content.location: Right of the boulder, on the prow. Hence the name.

content.description: Easliy protected and home to a few fun problems with room for variation. Although its been done it is not recommended for various reasons, one can jump off the rock further downstream into the water below. At your own risk though. Don't be suing a homeboy.
